Calculus can be studied with different levels of rigor. We can use 
informal descriptions, pictures, and examples, and discuss a lot of
important and meaningful things relying on our intuition and existing notions about 
the world. For example, for a lot of applications, it is sufficient to understand
that an integral is the area under a graph of a function, and it is not necessary to 
know the formal definition or the proofs of related theorems - we only need the natural
and familiar properties of areas.
