Being an introduction to serious mathematics the calculus course shows
the connection between intuitive, imaginative mathematical thinking and
working with formal statements. These two modes of thinking complement each other.
Without intuition, we cannot invent anything new, but intuition can deceive us.
To check it we write down careful proofs and check that every step is correct.
The opposite is also true: without intuition and correct mental images of 
mathematical objects we can easily miss a mistake in reasoning.
The real understanding of a proof happens not when we checked every line of it, 
but when we have a in our mind a clear picture of how it works altogether.
